### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

When migrating an application with lazy-loaded modules, a fairly recurrent pattern is encountered:

app.routes.ts
```ts
export const routes = [
  {
     path: 'admin',
     loadChildren: () =>
      import('./admin/admin.module').then(m => m.AdminModule)
   }
];
```

admin.module.ts
```ts
imports: [RouterModule.forChild(adminRoutes)]
```

admin.routes.ts
```ts
export const adminRoutes = [
  { path: '', component: AdminComponent }
]
```

Currently, the migration does not touch `RouterModule.forChild()` calls. This then prevents the `prune-ng-module` step to remove the module.

### Proposed solution

It would be great to migrate `app.routes.ts` to:

```ts
export const routes = [
  {
     path: 'admin',
     loadChildren: () =>
      import('./admin/admin.routes').then(m => m.adminRoutes)
   }
];
```

and remove `RouterModule.forChild(adminRoutes)` form `admin.module.ts`

### Alternatives considered

The migration can be done manually.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

forms

### Description

Hello Angular Team,

I came across a problem, where I have 
Parent and child components, where the child components are in `OnPush` state.
The Child component is generating a form and emits it to the parent component
We have a `Submit` button in the Parent component, and when we are submitting the form, at first it is checking the validity of the form, and if the form is invalid it is marking all of the fields as touched.
So as the change detection of the Child is `OnPush` it is not displaying any errors.

So I am thinking, maybe we can have a `errorChanges` like as `valueChanges` and `statusChanges` that will help us to easily use it in the template by the `async` pipe?

### Proposed solution

I have almost the same idea about its realisation.

```typescript
class FormControl extends AbstractControl {
   //.......................
   //.......................
   //.......................
   
   
   public get errorChanges(): Observable<ValidationErrors | null> {
      return this.valueChanges.
         pipe(
            startWith(this.value),
            mapTo(this.errors),
            disctinctUntilChanged((prevState, currentState) => {
                const prevErrors =  Object. getOwnPropertyNames(prevState || {});
                const newErrors =  Object. getOwnPropertyNames(currentState || {});
                const errorsList = new Set([...prevErrors, ...newErrors]);
              
                for(let error of errorsList) {
                     if(prevErrors[error] !== newErrors[error]) {
                         return true;
                     }
                } 
                
                return false;
            })
         );
   }
}

```

